I actually have previously watched a documentary about this case but decided to watch MrBallen's video just to see how he told the story. There are a few pieces of information I want to add from what I remember from the documentary. 

I remember from the documentary that they had mentioned that the area they wanted to hike in was very dangerous, not just the conditions of the hike but the possibility of other people being inside the dense vegetation. There apparently had been other murders not far from where they were hiking that were "unrelated". The theory with the photos being taken in the dark was done so the girls could see where they were going, they were using the light from the flash to see where to go which is why the photos seem very strange because they weren't actually taking photos, just using the light (OR their murderer took the photos to confuse investigators). 

Another part of the story is the failed attempts to log in to the phone. It was theorized that the girl who owned the phone fell down into a ravine and the other girl was trying to get into her phone to call for help but didn't know her passcode, and that's why there were so many failed attempts. OR their murderer tried to throw off investigators by making it appear that they were still alive after they had been taken or murdered. 

Their remains were also extremely strange and suspicious. The only parts of Kris that were found were part of her pelvic bone and one of her rib bones with no flesh attached, completely clean and bleached. Traces of phosphorous were found in the bones, which when samples were taken of the area the bones were found, no traces of phosphorus were found, meaning they were intentionally chemically cleaned with phosphorous. Also, in addition to there being no blood found (the water would have washed away some blood but bone marrow is the longest surviving tissue and the last to decompose), the bones were found on the shore, and since bones are denser than water, they would have surely sunk and gotten caught in some rocks in the "snake-like" river they were found on the bank of. Instead, they were placed in the same general area as the other remains (which is very unlikely due to the shape of the river). 

For Lisanne, they found a chunk of flesh that still had larvae in it, and appeared to be in the "second stage" of decomposition, which is radically different from the state in which Kris's bones were. Also from Lisanne, they found her femur, shin bone, and left foot (which was still inside her hiking shoe), all with flesh attached and bone marrow inside. The cuts were clean and not jagged like you would expect if it was an animal or an accident. I'm not an expert, this is just what I remember plus some quick googling to make sure I said the right things. Overall, definitely does not appear to be an accident.

Well, you did invite speculation, and so here goes two strong possibilities.  A -- The girls were targeted.  Probably by someone who encountered them at the Hostel, given that the dog was allowed to go home, when the girls were not.  Dogs are social creatures, and it wouldn't have just walked away from them to head on home if it got bored -- not if it had bothered to go with them into the jungle to begin with.  They could have followed the dog home safely even if they had gotten lost, if they'd been allowed to, so they most likely were not, and the dog was driven away when the killer took them.  Their killer chose them, and chose the time when he could take them carefully -- Foreign travelers, alone or in pairs, give a killer a whole lot of time to muddy the trail before the investigation can begin.  Also, jurisdiction is always a clown shower when more than one state department or embassy has to get involved.  

The girls' choice to take a long hike with no guide is notable as a particularly good opportunity for anyone who knows the local area, who wanted to be sure they'd get a chance to encounter the girls alone.  And, assuming their assailant had a firearm, or possibly more than one attacker, getting control of two young women in an environment they don't know well would not be difficult.

Scenario the second -- they accidentally wandered into a drug operation.  Personally, I feel that is the most likely.  Again, the lack of a guide who'd be able to steer them clear of the dangerous territory would have made it entirely possible for them to stumble into a coca or hemp plantation in the highlands, and from there, to be doomed.  This scenario has for the girls being kept prisoner for several days, while their captors debate whether ransoming them is worthwhile (as ransom for profit has been an industry in central america for awhile now) but eventually deciding that the risk is too great.  It would also account for the other remains found in the area as the inevitable casualties that an illegal drug operation tends to create.  

I think that nobody in the village spoke up because whoever the predator/perpetrator is, they are very well known, and very deeply feared there, and are so secure in their power that people who have to live there are not willing to risk going against them.  Because when certain types of bullies take over a place, everyone knows that no amount of money is worth the risk.

I think as for the bones appearing not to have been subject to animal predation, there are a few ways that could be accomplished -- none of them nice.  If the bodies were left in a body of water, then fish and crabs could clear the bones without leaving distress marks, and similarly if they were left on an exposed high outcrop, birds could have done the same.  Also, the flesh could just have been cooked off the bones, which would then be discarded -- which is horrible, yes, but also you pointed out that the destination of their hike was a volcano, and boiling streams and pools can happen with those.  

I definitely agree that the girls' disappearance was not a simple case of getting lost and dying from mischance.  The dog, the backpack, and the phone records nail that down for me.

I am a photographer who while on a trip to a dark zone (Lake Powell, Utah), decided to try my luck at some landscapes with the milky way.  I scoped out a spot during the afternoon that was literally 50 yards from our camp on the shoreline but a 1/4 mile hike because the camp was at the base of a canyon.  I found an easy path up and down the steep canyon walls that involved just a bit of scrambling, but I did it in flip flops multiple times and was ready.  Golden hour hits, I hike to the rim and post up, I start taking photo after photo into the night.  I am excited because it's the last night and every single night before, just as the sky would get dark enough for the milky way, the full moon would rise.  This was the first night that it would stay below the horizon long enough to shoot the milky way.  So it's like 12 am by the time the moon is lighting up the entire back and foreground so I decide to pack up and head back.  But then I instantly realize I have a problem.  I am standing in the shadow of a giant sandstone butte and I can barely see a thing.  I get back to the general area where I knew the little path back down was but I could not find it.  I walked back and forth for 20 minutes and started to get impatient.  I was about to just go for it and so glad I didn't before I had an idea.  My camera does not have a flash, a Nikon D780 and I had a wide angle f2.8.  I thought at first the screen would be bright enough to show me the way but it did nothing.  Finally I just cranked the ISO way up and took a few 10 or 20 second exposures and I turned night into daylight.  I could now see that I was standing directly above a 50 foot drop and that my path was further back the way I had came.  Snapping pics all along the way, I had no doubt now where I was going and I could suddenly see in the dark.

Around the same time I went into the amazon basin alone to visit a tribe, there are 1000 ways to die.

comments.text:
I'll tell you a story about how strange things can become when u travel. In 1981, I was nineteen and found myself serving in the Canadian Military. On a whim, I decided to backpack through England, travel around up to Scotland, Ireland, and then finally on to Paris France. The night before I was leaving, this guy named Perry who had a room down from mine in CFB Trenton, asked me if I was interested in doing a psychic reading on my trip.

 I was fascinated and decided yeah, anything helps as I was slightly nervous about attempting this trip on my own after my two military buddies decided to take a pass on this month-long experience fair enough, not exactly for the faint of heart in those pre-internet social media days

As I recall, Perry stated that he cannot remember what he says in a trance, so I should listen intently. Perry tells me I am going to have a good time, not a great time, true. And that I was going to meet a dark-haired woman on the train through Switzerland. That she would want me to go with her, but if I did, I would never come home alive.

 I listened intently, thinking, well, I never intended to travel there anyway, so WTF? and when he came out of his trance, he asked me what he had said. I told him, and he stated, that I should listen to every word, as he was never wrong. I had no idea, just how accurate, the man would be in his predictions

Well fast track to the trip. While crossing the Atlantic, we were informed that London had an ongoing air traffic controllers strike and that we would be diverting to a Canadian Military Base in what was then called West Germany. At this point, I was so absorbed by the sudden changes, I completely forgot what Perry had said. So I leave West Germany, changed my travel plans, and on to Holland, Denmark, and Sweden, then back to Denmark, and finally on to Austria.

I leave Innsbruck Austra with far less dinero. and after three weeks of humid heat, beautiful women, and meeting some of the most bizarre characters on those pre-internet travels through mainland Europe, I decided after my two thousandth village view, that I would cap it off on a final trip to Paris, via Geneva. Great ending until I was approached by a dark-haired woman

By this time, having drunk more booze than most nineteen-year-old college students in their freshmen hazing days, I had totally forgotten Perry's words, I say hi. She asks me where I am going, and if I wanted to perhaps? stop off, and spend some time with her. Now again, I was nineteen, horny as hell, but she wasn't really all that hot, a solid six-plus at best, maybe? 

She reminded me of the dark-haired girl in the old Scooby-Doo cartoons kind of look. Train stops in I believe Lucerne? changing trains for Geneva. Waiting, she starts to walk up the tracks at a frantic pace. I say it's cool, I can just leave, no problems really. Then she gets really aggressive and says no, you stay here. I am like, fuck you, lady, seriously. what's with the attitude man? 

To this day, I distinctly remember looking at the front of the train, as she was standing on my left then Perry's voice rings loud in my head. I dodge the future serial killer and boot it onto the train for Geneva. I look out, and she is walking up the tracks with some guy, pissed off as fuck. Now I come from a rather Cajun-style family background. Ghosts, hauntings, the whole deal, so I am very open-minded to the strange things that can happen in life. Reflecting upon this experience, was one I never forgot, believe me. 

When I return back to the base in Canada in seven days' time, Perry invites me into his room, and I quietly told him what happened over a few more beers. He freaks out, and said, "I am never wrong. If you would have gone with her, you would never have returned home." This is why, over forty-one years later, you always go with your gut instinct

Honestly, the scariest travel encounter I've ever come across. Up until this happened, the trip was amazing, I met so many bizarre and fascinating people riding the trains. One guy was a former sniper with the Australian Army, who had served in Vietnam. Looked like Charles Manson. The dude had been riding the rails through Europe endlessly, for ten years, strung out on PTSD. A SOMEWHAT LONG, BUT TRUE STORY even to this day, I still often think about that encounter, in how it could have all gone?

comments.text: 5 Years later, someone has explained the photos without much room for doubt. They were signalling towards Boquette, and the branch with the red plastic bag was also a signal, to mark their campsite in case someone came across their campsite and didn't see them behind the boulders they were using for shelter. It's very likely they couldn't sleep during the night due to the drop in temps and had to sleep during the day. Honestly, this is one of the saddest stories I have encountered, second only to the Titanic. It will never leave my head, it will never leave my heart. Just like the gentlemen that sank with the ship, so did the girls set up a final camp on the 8th, knowing they will most likely never be found. Kris carrying Lisanne on her shoulders, setting up a final SOS alongside the bottom of the pringles can in case it reflects off of something. She never left her friend. They sat together on a rock sending flash signals into the sky the same way the doomed operators of the Marconi room sent S.O.S until the ships power went out. Eventually they both died. Probably Lisanne first, since she had a broken ankle and infected foot. I honestly can't imagine those final days on that embankment. I wish they were afforded the same luxury as the gentlemen that chose to go down with the ship. A fine brandy to tide over deaths cold grasp as they passed on from this world. They deserved better. They all deserved better; but since life dealt them an unbelievably shitty hand that collapsed their entire lives out of nowhere... like I said... wish they could have at least had a brandy to live out their final moments in peace.

You'd see Kris play with the camera and probably say something funny as she takes a picture of Lisanne studying the map, looking up at her with playful derision. I wonder what it is they talked about thru the fields on the way to the forest. The fly on that day would hear them talk about what they would do in Boquete the upcoming weeks, they're life back home, they're families, they're boyfriends... you'd hear Lisanne explain to Kris what route they were taking to the summit and what they would see along the way. You'd hear them joke and complain and probably a few high pitch shreaks as one of them slipped on the trail, followed shortly by laughter. At the top you'd see Lisanne hand Kris the camera and tell her to make sure she get's a good panoramic view of the mountains behind as she makes a face and points to it. A few seconds later you'd hear Kris say something along the lines of 'me too' as she gives Lisanne the camera back and strikes a pose of her own. You'd hear them discuss going further down the trail on the other side of the mirador. That mystery which has been haunting so many people for over a decade would finally be solved once and for all. You'd see Kris's mood slowly change from happy and enthusiastic to tired and eventually worried and scared. You'd see photo 509 as it's taken. You'd see it slowly get dark, you'd see them leave the trail, get lost and call for help. You'd see them spend the first night in the jungle and the distress in their eyes when the next morning the sun comes up but they are no closer to finding the trail. You'd follow them as they wander further and further towards a river of false hope, you'd see Lisanne break her foot, you'd see them walk for days and days getting nowhere...You'd hear them slowly make their peace with death as they realize no one is coming. You'd sit idly by as they sit huddled together on a rock in the middle of a downpour, taking pictures of the darkness that surrounds them. You'd be there as they take their final breaths, and you'd finally understand with no uncertainty where they were, how they got there and why they couldn't get out. Those are the things that truthfully, I would be terrified of seeing but after all these years... I'm a fly on a leaf as I listen to Kris and Lisanne argue and try to rationalize their situation because I finally saw that fateful wrong turn, that misplaced step that after so many years finally makes it all make sense. I don't have to guess or theorize or stay up anymore reading dead end theories one after the other which all lead back to the beginning of a giant maze. In a way, I too stepped into the jungle with them after hearing their story... and just like them, I fear that I too may never leave.

comments.text:
I've been lost in a forest/bush at night, and this just makes those memories feel so fresh. too, 
I was with a friend too, thankfully, and there was a full moon to keep the bush around me lit up which helped a ton. I used my phone's compass, without reception, that ultimately got me through 5 hours of being lost when I found the road leading back to our campsite and car. We were only late teens.

To anyone curious to know what an experience like this may feel like, well, I'll try my best:

It's like your body and mind is stretching back thousands of years to some prehistoric time where all you relied on was your senses. All of these senses were alive and in full gear. I was beyond scared. It was more survival mode had kicked in. It also felt like my consciousness was taking a back seat. Like I wasn't really in control. I was just sitting back, watching a terrifying movies, wondering what I'll do to surive. I was sensitive to every shape and every sound. At one point, I came across a kangaroo that surprised me - the adrenaline, fear and strength that came over me in that moment was astounding. It was genuine flight or fight. I felt as if I could run at it, push it down, pound it, and rip out its heart. Or, I felt ready to scream and roar and yell. Eventually, I calmed down as they are really quite harmless creatures and was just as scared as me haha. But to experience all of those emotions in that short time of first seeing it was a lot. I got out of there finally, around 5 hours later, of constant confusion and walking in circles. We kept missing the road somehow which added another hour to our already long and gone-wrong hike. When you're out there, everything looks the same. Orientation goes quickly. I still don't understand how we got lost or how we got back. The memories still make me shiver, and so seeing these pictures scared me to my bones. 

A side note to anyone thinking this may be exaggeration and that it's not worth comparing to with the unfortunate case of the two girls... Yes, my experience was merely a sliver of what they went through. My experience was significantly different. However, in case you aren't aware. The Australian bush where I lived can be dangerous - and mostly in context to humans. I lived near an area with dense, unexplored mountainous bush (north-east-central Victoria) and gold mine territory. We would always be told stories of those who fall down mines and never return. There are countless mines out there that are unregulated by national parks because sometimes they're just not known about or easily accessible. Near where we were camped, there were holes covered in scrub that would go down until darkness. You did not want to fall into them. They were hard to see. Additionally, my part of country Victoria is haunted with a past of murder and serial killers where campers get taken and killed. All us local kids were well aware of the stories. I've been on a few isolated camps where my mate and I (as very young adults) would sit frozen in our swags, holding our breaths and with no light or sound on, in the middle of the night, as we watch an individual (always different) walk unknowingly just outside our spot, alone, through what is very isolated bush, and off into the distance. This was a regular occurrence. Not saying they were the type, but the risk is certainly there. 

Now that I'm a few years old and with a finance in my life, I honestly can't believe the amount of testosterone and sheer lack of intelligence that I possessed to think that it was okay to do that as an after school hobby.
